<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="212" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[113,752,193,248]" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,259,193,217]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">Etymology. –</emphasis>
The name of the species is derived from the type-locality.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="212" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[113,752,289,408]" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,251,289,313]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">Diagnosis. –</emphasis>
Small blackish species with all bristles black, wing clear with median veins almost not visible, fore tibia deformed with about 6 spine-like anterodorsal bristles in basal half not longer than tibia depth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="213" pageId="1" pageNumber="212" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[113,753,449,568]" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis box="[113,418,449,473]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,353,449,473]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">Description. – Male –</emphasis>
Head
</emphasis>
. Occiput, antenna dark brown, second and third flagellomeres aristiform. Face blackish. Palpus apparently brown. Labrum length about twice head height.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[812,1452,193,568]" lastBlockId="2.[136,776,193,376]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="213" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis box="[812,892,193,216]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">Thorax</emphasis>
brown, scutum subshiny. Acrostichals missing; dorsocentrals uniserial ending with 1 strong, long bristle in prescutellar depression. 
<emphasis box="[1072,1123,257,280]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">Legs</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1136,1218,257,280]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[113,149,2063,2084]" captionTargetBox="[117,1448,682,1971]" captionTargetId="figure-9@1.[102,1460,631,1988]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1. Male fore leg in frontal view: A, tibia and first tarsomere of E. (C.) neesoonensis; B, tibia and tarsus of E. (C.) producta; C, tibia and first tarsomere of E. (C.) tortuosa; D, tibia and first tarsomere of E. (C.) verruca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4619640" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4619640/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
) brown. Left mid and hind legs missing. All femora with rather short bristles. Fore tibia deformed, somewhat S-shaped with about 6 spine-like anterodorsal bristles in basal half; first fore tarsomere with 1 strong, long anterolateral bristle at base. Mid tibia with 3 strong, rather long dorsal bristles (at basal quarter, about at middle, at tip); first mid tarsomere with 1 strong, long anterodorsal bristle at apical tip. Hind tibia swollen apically with strong, long dorsal bristles, several distinct ventral bristles at apical half; hind tarsus swollen, first four tarsomeres with long dorsal bristles. 
<emphasis box="[394,450,193,216]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">Wing</emphasis>
(length = 
<quantity box="[553,634,193,216]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="2" pageNumber="213" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
) clear. Discal cell and median veins almost not visible. A1 abbreviated. Halter brown. 
<emphasis box="[288,389,257,280]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">Abdomen</emphasis>
brown, sternites with pair of distinct bristles posteriorly. 
<emphasis box="[378,524,289,312]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">Hypopygium</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[545,621,289,312]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,172,2093,2114]" captionTargetBox="[144,1464,1104,2005]" captionTargetId="figure-25@2.[113,1493,1063,2049]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Male hypopygium of E. (C.) neesoonensis, lateral view. Scale = 4.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4619642" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4619642/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="213">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Epandrium triangular with strong, long bristles at tip. Hypandrium pointed. Phallus thin.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4619640" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4619640" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4619640/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="212" startId="1.[113,149,2063,2084]" targetBox="[117,1448,682,1971]" targetPageId="1">
